    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[Er69b] Erd\\H{o}s, P., Problems and results in chromatic graph theory. Proof Techniques in Graph Theory (Proc. Second Ann\nArbor Graph Theory Conf., Ann Arbor, Mich.,\n1968) (1969), 27-35.",
      "remarks": "This question was inspired by a theorem of Babai, that if $G$ is a graph on a well-ordered set with chromatic number $\\geq \\aleph_0$ there is a subgraph on vertices with order-type $\\omega$ with chromatic number $\\aleph_0$.\n\nErd\\H{o}s and Hajnal showed this does not generalise to higher cardinals - they (see \\cite{Er69b}) constructed a set on $\\omega_1^2$ with chromatic number $\\aleph_1$ such that every strictly smaller subgraph has chromatic number $\\leq \\aleph_0$ as follows: the vertices of $G$ are the pairs $(x_\\alpha,y_\\beta)$ for $1\\leq \\alpha,\\beta <\\omega_1$, ordered lexicographically. We connect $(x_{\\alpha_1},y_{\\beta_1})$ and $(x_{\\alpha_2},y_{\\beta_2})$ if and only if $\\alpha_1<\\alpha_2$ and $\\beta_1<\\beta_2$.\n\nA similar construction produces a graph on $\\omega_2^2$ with chromatic number $\\aleph_2$ such that every smaller subgraph has chromatic number $\\leq \\aleph_1$."
    },
    "source_state": "open",
    "tags": [
      "graph theory",
      "chromatic number"
    ]
  },
